                <span itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Morning Agenda: Pfizer&#8217;s War on Taxation</span>
                <span class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
                    By Amie Tsang                </span>
                <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-12-01T11:02:02+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">December 1, 2015 6:02 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">December 1, 2015 6:02 am</span>            </div>
			<div class="entry-content">
			<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//news.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/12/01/morning-agenda-pfizers-war-on-taxation/" data-title="Morning Agenda: Pfizer&#8217;s War on Taxation" data-description="New Banking Rules for New York | Court Upholds Award Against RBC Capital | New Fed Rule Limits Emergency Lending">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>PFIZERâS WAR ON TAXATION</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> As long as United States companies feel they have to <b>compete with companies in countries with lower tax rates</b>, they will seek ways to leave the country and reduce their bill, </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/12/01/business/dealbook/pfizers-long-war-on-taxation.html?ref=dealbook">Andrew Ross Sorkin writes in the DealBook column.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Pfizer was using strategies as far back as 1976</b> and long before it conceived of merging with Allergan. It set up shop in Puerto Rico to take advantage of a tax credit program intended to help spur investment there. A 1992 report showed that it had managed to save at least $759 million over 10 years. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When the tax break was phased out, Pfizer and its rivals pulled up their stakes, leading, in part, to the islandâs current economic crisis. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Pfizer has also received at least <b>$50 million in federal subsidies over nearly the last 15 years</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There are ideas circulating in Washington about how to make it less attractive for companies to leave the United States, but they are often short-term solutions that would require being more protectionist and could create unintended consequences. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The only way to end the inversion craze is to <b>reform the corporate tax code</b>, Mr. Sorkin argues. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As the White House says on its website, âOur system has one of the highest statutory tax rates among developed countries to generate about the same amount of corporate tax revenue as our developed country partners as a share of our economy; this, in turn, hurts our competitiveness in the world economy.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Companiesâ tax rates would probably fall, but the gap between rates in the United States and other developed countries <b>should not be so large that it drives American companies overseas</b>, Mr. Sorkin writes.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>NEW BANKING RULES FOR NEW YORK</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo is preparing new regulations for New York State banks aimed at <b>preventing flows of illicit money through Wall Street to militants and criminals</b>,<br />
<a HREF="//www.nytimes.com/2015/12/01/business/dealbook/new-york-proposes-new-banking-rules-to-staunch-flow-of-illicit-financing.html?ref=dealbook">Ben Protess reports in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Cuomo plans to propose rules this week that would give New York State banks <b>more responsibility to thwart money laundering and the financing of terrorist groups</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The rules would force a chief compliance officer to certify that a bank maintains systems to âdetect, weed out and prevent illicitâ money transfers. Officers that filed âincorrect or falseâ certification could face criminal charges. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The effort to block terrorist funding could prove challenging â <b>clients often hide behind layers of legitimate front groups</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The New York State Department of Financial Services has taken an aggressive stance on Wall Street, but its <b>money-laundering policy has gained traction since militants tied to Islamic State killed 130 people in Paris</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Islamic State earns tens of millions of dollars a month and could finance attacks around the world. The Treasury Department has placed sanctions on individuals and countries tied to the financing of militant attacks. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Banks will have 45 days to comment</b> on the proposal and some could mount legal challenges or abandon their New York State licenses. But some might welcome the new rules, which provide some clarity as they grapple with overlapping states and regulations. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>COURT UPHOLDS AWARD AGAINST RBC CAPITAL</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The Delaware Supreme Court upheld a $76 million damage award against RBC Capital Markets over its role in advising the ambulance service Rural/Metro in its sale to Warburg Pincus, </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a HREF="//www.nytimes.com/2015/12/01/business/dealbook/delaware-court-upholds-award-against-rbc-capital.html?ref=dealbook&#038;_r=0">Liz Moyer reports in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The case had highlighted the <b>close relationship between Wall Street investment bankers and the private equity firms they court for business</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The class action was filed in 2011 after Rural/Metroâs all-cash sale to Warburg for $438 million. The Delaware Court of Chancery concluded that RBC persuaded Rural/Metroâs board to accept Warburgâs offer <b>without telling the board that it was trying to win a role in Warburgâs financing of the transaction</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The decision will be a blow to Wall Street advisers, but the court was careful to point out that it was <b>not making a sweeping revision of rules regarding adviser conflicts</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIt is a nuanced opinion in which the court affirms the lower court decision, sends a <b>powerful message to disloyal investment banks</b>, but also provides investment banks with comfort, provided they act transparently and forthrightly,â said Andrew F. Tuch, an associate professor at the School of Law of Washington University in St. Louis. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Investors still have to prove that an adviser acted with intent. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The <b>Manufacturing ISM Report on Business</b> will be published at 10 a.m. <b>Charles L. Evans</b>, the president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago, will speak to the Lansing Regional Chamber of Commerce in Michigan at 11:30 a.m.  <b>Lael Brainard</b>, a Federal Reserve governor, will speak about the lower neutral rate at the Stanford Institute for Economic Policy Research Associates Meeting at 8 p.m. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>NEW FED RULE LIMITS EMERGENCY LENDING</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> In the lead-up to the financial crisis of 2008, the Federal Reserve had the ability to make huge emergency loans to almost any entity it chose. Now it has adopted a rule <b>restricting its extraordinary financial powers</b>,<br />
<a HREF="//www.nytimes.com/2015/12/01/business/dealbook/new-fed-rule-limits-emergency-lending-power.html?ref=dealbook">Peter Eavis reports in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The five members of the Fedâs board voted on Monday to approve the rule, which takes effect on Jan. 1. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The rule addresses a <b>quandary in the financial system</b>. Some say that central banks need a free hand to lend liberally in a crisis so that panic cannot take down healthy firms. But others say this encourages banks to pursue the very habits that make the system unstable in the first place. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Dodd-Frank reforms tried to maintain the Fedâs latitude, while preventing banks from taking advantage of the Fedâs largesse. Dodd-Frank prevented the Fed from setting up a loan facility for just one firm. This, in theory, now makes a rescue like the 2008 bailout of American International Group illegal. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Dodd-Frank does, however, allow the Fed <b>to set up emergency loan facilities that many firms can tap</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Fedâs rule contains specific <b>measures to make sure insolvent companies are disqualified from the emergency loans</b>. It also says that an entity cannot borrow for the purpose of lending to an insolvent entity. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Consumer advocates say the rule could still allow seriously stressed firms to borrow from the Fed. The one or two banks that are most desperate for assistance could effectively be obtaining a bailout on the sly through the loan facility. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And solvency can be difficult to determine, especially during a crisis, though the new rule says <b>the Fed must obtain evidence that borrowing firms are not insolvent</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Members of Congress may have more to say on the matter. Senator Elizabeth Warren, Democrat of Massachusetts, said that &#8220;<b>there are still loopholes that the Fed could exploit to provide another backdoor bailout to giant financial institutions.</b>&#8220;</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></div>
</div>
